ries covering all the message and property IDs, but the knowledge file condenses this to four entries—omitting PROP0001 and PROP0003, though these are just illustrative examples of the pattern so the simplification is reasonable.\n\nFor the second method using class and property names, the source demonstrates the full User class with varying validation constraints on each property, but the knowledge file appears to show only a partial example...\n\nChecking for fabrications now...\n\nThe knowledge file states that when a subclass overrides a method with one or more validation annotations, those new conditions replace the inherited ones entirely. Looking at the source material, it confirms this behavior—when User's setName method is overridden with @Required and @Length annotations, those specific conditions are what get used for validation, not the parent class conditions. This checks out. 条件が置き換わることを確認できた。知識ファイルの説明は正確で、オーバーライド時に1つ以上のバリデーションアノテーションを指定すると、親クラスの条件は新しい条件に置き換わる。コード例のコメントも、@Requiredを外すことで必須入力チェックが削除されることを示しており、これは置き換わりの動作を正しく反映している。\n\nChildEntityの例を見直すと、知識ファイルは@Digits（コンバータ）が親から継承され、@NumberRange（バリデーション）が追加されると説明しているが、ソースを確認する必要がある。\n\nContinuing to verify the inheritance behavior... @Digits is a converter annotation that gets inherited regardless, while @NumberRange is a validation annotation that gets added on the child class to enforce additional constraints on the value.\n\nNow I'm checking the section structure of the documentation. The automated warning flags a mismatch between the expected section count and what's actually in the source — I'm counting the RST headings to verify whether the documentation is properly organized. it into 3 separate knowledge sections might not be warranted. But checking the rule more carefully—if an h2 section has 2000+ characters of plain text and contains h3 headings that aren't split into separate knowledge sections, I should flag it. Looking at the \"国際化したプロパティの表示名称の取得方法\" section, it's quite substantial with multiple code examples, tables, and configuration details across its subsections, so it likely exceeds that threshold and should be split accordingly. The h2 section contains substantial content across three h3 subsections—multiple code examples with 30+ line classes, tables with 9 rows each, and XML configuration—easily exceeding 2000 characters of plain text. Since the knowledge file doesn't further subdivide this content despite the h3 structure existing, this appears to be a reportable case under the V3 rule. Let me verify whether the knowledge section actually covers all this h3 content or if there's a gap in the split. So this is a structural issue I should flag as a section_issue with minor severity. Now I'm moving on to check the hints completeness for each section, starting with s1 where I'm verifying that all the key entities, annotations, and inheritance concepts are properly documented.\n\nFor s2, the hints look solid overall—ValidationManager and the internationalization concepts are covered. The User class reference is already captured in s1, and while specific message IDs like MSG00001 appear in the examples, those don't need to be separate hints since the pattern is clear.\n\nNow I'm checking the structure of section 3 and noticing the \"国際化したプロパティの表示名称の取得方法\" heading is quite long with multiple subsections underneath it, which might need some reorganization. but the knowledge file only includes a subset of those entries—it shows the core message keys with both language variants, which captures the essential pattern even if it's not exhaustive. The simplified examples in the knowledge file seem intentional rather than incomplete, focusing on demonstrating the methodology rather than reproducing every single entry from the source.\n\nNow I'm checking for actual discrepancies between what the source says and what the knowledge file claims. The main issue I'm spotting is in the V3 section structure—the second section has a large heading with three subsecti